Wishing you love, light, and happiness.

snippet.textDisplay:
Jaclyn baby, I don’t know what I feel about when you said “millions of people turn to prescription drugs an alcohol in hard times, you’re not alone, it doesn’t make you crazy, doesn’t make you an addict....” as a recovering addict, I do kinda resent that. I mean, not for the sake of mindless critique though, I’m just mentioning it because the first step is always admitting you have a problem. Uncontrollable self-medication using substances is definitely indication of a problem. That’s textbook substance abuse. If you can’t stop, if you’ve become dependent on a substance, then that is indicative of addiction. If that’s the case, nobody ever did themselves any favors by saying “I have a problem I need to work on, but it’s not like I’m an addict or anything” - that’s denial. First step, admit you have a problem. Those who refuse to admit the severity of their substance abuse and dependence aren’t really setting up the best building blocks for eliminating those behaviors. Often we say “i am self-medicating and I know that’s bad, but I’m not an addict of anything” because we want to stop the bad behavior, but we don’t want to close the door to substances entirely. And that’s not all that helpful to getting help either.
It’s just food for thought my love. I think you’re very brave for coming out with your truth, but I simply don’t think it’s wise to put self-medication on a pedestal above addiction. I related to your story, I’m a recovering addict. I’ve heard your kind of story from many others in groups. My addiction stemmed from self medication. Often, that’s what addiction looks like. Addiction is not just sucking D for crack in dark alleyways in dirty cities, it’s something that looks very different from person to person, but it’s all valid, it’s all a problem we need to fix, and the first step to fixing that is always gonna be taking ownership of that problem, admitting you have a problem, and not making excuses or saying those people over there have a worse problem, my substance abuse is only a 5 and the heroin addict over there, they’re a 10. Nope. We’re all addicts. We all have a problem. That problem looks very different person to person. That’s very normal. But seeing yourself in the same category as those of us who have done way more awful things to ourselves and others in the name of addiction is often the wake up call people need to get help. Realizing you’re no better (nor worse) than the “crackhead” you may look down upon, and if you don’t get clean that could easily become you.....often that realization is essential to healing. Just something worth thinking about :)
